<h2>Update 31G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Treatment of leave payments - pensions. See guideline 27.8620.</p>
<p>This amendment states that paid leave must be taken into account when determining the rate of pension payable.</p>
<h2>Update 30G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Amendment to table of contents to reflect update 31G.</p>
<h2>Update 29G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Earned income free area. See guidelines 27.23000 to 27.23130.</p>
<p>The "Investing in the Nation" statement (February 1993) announced from 20 September 1993 an introduction of an earnings free area of $30.00 pf for single people and an increase from $30.00 to $50.00 pf. in the earnings free area for each member of a couple. Changes to the earned income free area will assist in increasing the number of clients and their partners gaining employment providing a basis for a transition to full-time employment. It provides a financial incentive for employment and directs the benefits of income test liberalisation away from those with substantial income from investments.</p>
<h2>Update 28G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Changes to additional earnings free area. See guideline 27.2950.</p>
<p>The "Investing in the Nation" statement (February 1993) announced from 20 September 1993 an introduction of an earnings free area of $30.00 pf for single people and an increase from $30.00 to $50.00 pf. in the earnings free area for each member of a couple. Changes to the earned income free area will assist in increasing the number of clients and their partners gaining employment providing a basis for a transition to full-time employment. It provides a financial incentive for employment and directs the benefits of income test liberalisation away from those with substantial income from investments.</p>
<h2>Update 27G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 14 - SICKNESS ALLOWANCE - Waiving the ordinary waiting period. See guidelines 14.6800 to 14.6801.</p>
<p>The "Investing in the Nation" statement (February 1993) announced changes simplifying the waiver of the ordinary waiting period. From 20 September 1993 a single provision replaces several existing provisions for waiving the ordinary waiting period. Simplifying waiver provisions assists both clients and staff by making conditions of eligibility easier to explain and understand. It provides further incentive to do casual and / or insecure employment.</p>
<h2>Update 26G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Waiving the ordinary waiting period. See guideline 12.6500.</p>
<p>The "Investing in the Nation" statement (February 1993) announced changes simplifying the waiver of the ordinary waiting period. From 20 September 1993 a single provision replaces several existing provisions for waiving the ordinary waiting period. Simplifying waiver provisions assists both clients and staff by making conditions of eligibility easier to explain and understand. It provides further incentive to do casual and / or insecure employment.</p>
<h2>Update 25G # Date 23 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Waiving the ordinary waiting period. See guidelines 12.6000 to 12.6003.</p>
<p>The "Investing in the Nation" statement (February 1993) announced changes simplifying the waiver of the ordinary waiting period. From 20 September 1993 a single provision replaces several existing provisions for waiving the ordinary waiting period. Simplifying waiver provisions assists both clients and staff by making conditions of eligibility easier to explain and understand. It provides further incentive to do casual and/or insecure employment.</p>
<h2 id="2september1993">Update 24G # Date 2 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 6 - DISABILITY SUPPORT PENSION - Abolition of second impairment assessments. Guidelines 6.500 to 6.509 (deleted).</p>
<p>Prior to 26 July 1993, any person found not to qualify for DSP following examination by a CMO or AMP because of an impairment rating of 10% or 15% were offered the option of a second medical assessment by another CMO or AMP. If an impairment rating of 20% or more was allocated at the second assessment, determination of the application for DSP proceeded. From 26 July 1993 clients will no longer be offered the option of a second assessment of their impairment rating, but any offers made prior to that date will be honoured.</p>
<h2>Update 23G # Date 2 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 6 - DISABILITY SUPPORT PENSION - Amendment to table of contents to reflect update 24G.</p>
<h2>Update 22G # Date 2 September 1993</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 23 - ADDITIONAL PAYMENTS - RENT ASSISTANCE, INCENTIVE ALLOWANCE, PHARMACEUTICAL ALLOWANCE, TELEPHONE ALLOWANCE - Remote area allowance. See guidelines 23.6000 to 23.7201.</p>
<p>This amendment sets out policy guidelines and eligibility criteria for remote area allowance. Details cover eligibility guidelines, points to be used to determine 'usual place of residence', temporary absence from a remote area and taxation issues.</p>
